s, Underhill, Osborne, Jordan, Derville, corporals Wenzel, Myer, **Private George B. Stanley 'B' company**, others noted. KIA Aug 30, 1862 at Second Battle of Bull Run (Manassas) when the 13th NY along with 18th MA and 1st MI charged across open fields under heavy musketry, shells, and canister from three sides, reaching within thirty yards of the Confederate line. Reinforcements unable to stand the fire fell back; the 13th NY 'fought with desperation, but in vain.' EH 3616 incorrectly gives death date as Aug 3, 1862 — corrected per Sam's research source (13th NYSV regimental history).","battles":["BTL045"]}],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909, entry 3616"},{"short":"Sam's research: 'Brief Account of the 13th New York State Volunteers' (libraryweb.org)"},{"short":"Civil War letters of Pvt. George B. Stanley published in The Upstate Journal of New York"}],"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[],"primary_url":"https://www.libraryweb.org/~digitized/books/Brief_Account_of_the_13th_New_York_State_Volunteers.pdf","primary_url_label":"13th NYSV regimental history (libraryweb.org)"},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Killed at Second Bull Run, age twenty-six","body":"Pvt. George B. Stanley served in Company B of the 13th New York State Volunteer Infantry. He earned mention in the regimental history for meritorious conduct during the Seven Days Battles in July 1862."},{"number":2,"category":"archive","header":"His Civil War letters survive in print","body":"Pvt. Stanley's wartime letters home appear monthly in The Upstate Journal of New York, providing a Union soldier's perspective on the early days of the war. His unit became part of the Army of the Potomac, which formed after First Manassas in July 1861 and would clash with the Confederate Army of Northern Virginia for nearly four years."}],"cross_connections":[],"cross_reference":{"edward_hooker_1909":"3616"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[]